message_1:
Solve the following system of linear equations using Jacobi iterative method: 

\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
2x + y + z &= 3 \\
x + 3y + z &= 6 \\
x + y + 4z &= 8 \\
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

With initial guesses $x_0=0, y_0=0, z_0=0$ and accuracy of the solution up to three decimal places.

message_2:
To solve the given system of linear equations using the Jacobi iterative method, we first rewrite the equations in the form of x, y, and z:

\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
x &= \frac{3 - y - z}{2} \\
y &= \frac{6 - x - z}{3} \\
z &= \frac{8 - x - y}{4} \\
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

Now, we start with the initial guesses $x_0=0, y_0=0, z_0=0$ and iterate until the solution converges to the desired accuracy (up to three decimal places).

Iteration 1:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
x_1 &= \frac{3 - 0 - 0}{2} = 1.5 \\
y_1 &= \frac{6 - 0 - 0}{3} = 2 \\
z_1 &= \frac{8 - 0 - 0}{4} = 2 \\
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

Iteration 2:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
x_2 &= \frac{3 - 2 - 2}{2} = -0.5 \\
y_2 &= \frac{6 - 1.5 - 2}{3} = 0.833 \\
z_2 &= \frac{8 - 1.5 - 2}{4} = 1.125 \\
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

Iteration 3:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
x_3 &= \frac{3 - 0.833 - 1.125}{2} = 0.521 \\
y_3 &= \frac{6 - (-0.5) - 1.125}{3} = 1.792 \\
z_3 &= \frac{8 - (-0.5) - 0.833}{4} = 1.667 \\
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

We continue this process until the difference between consecutive iterations is less than the desired accuracy (0.001). After several iterations, we obtain the following approximate solutions:

\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
x &\approx 0.999 \\
y &\approx 1.998 \\
z &\approx 1.999 \\
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

Thus, the solution to the given system of linear equations using the Jacobi iterative method with an accuracy of up to three decimal places is approximately $x \approx 0.999, y \approx 1.998, z \approx 1.999$.
